# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: inquirer-prompts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] The term **asynchronous** refers to two or more objects or events that do not exist or happen at the same time, that is, they are **not** synchronous.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] When multiple related things happen without any being dependent on the completion of previous happenings, they are asynchronous.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] In computing, the word "asynchronous" is used in two major contexts, as explained below.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] Asynchronous communication is a method of exchanging messages in which the sending, receiving, and processing of each message is not dependent on the sending, receipt, or processing of other messages.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] In asynchronous communication, each party receives and processes messages when convenient or possible to do so, rather than doing so immediately upon receipt.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] Additionally, messages may be sent without waiting for acknowledgement, with the understanding that if a problem occurs, the recipient will request corrections or otherwise handle the situation.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] Email is a type of asynchronous human communication.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] The recipient reads the email and responds to it (or not) at their convenience, not necessarily right away.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] All parties can continue to send and receive messages at any time.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] Emails don't have to be scheduled in a particular sequence.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] In asynchronous software, making a request, such as to a server, does not block other processes while waiting for the response.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] The software can continue performing other tasks.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] For example, in promise-based APIs, `Promise` objects are created for long operations.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] After the operation is complete, the promise is handled.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] With promises, the software doesn't have to wait for the operation to finish.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] Asynchronous software design expands upon the concept by building code that allows a program to ask that a task be performed alongside the original task (or tasks), without stopping to wait for the task to complete.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] When the secondary task is completed, the original task is notified using an agreed-upon mechanism so that it knows the work is done, and that the result, if any, is available.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] There are a number of programming techniques for implementing asynchronous software.
[src:inquirer-prompts/asynchronous] See the article Asynchronous JavaScript for an introduction to them.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:inquirer-prompts/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
