[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The **`Promise`** object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To learn about the way promises work and how you can use them, we advise you to read Using promises first.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A `Promise` is a proxy for a value not necessarily known when the promise is created.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] It allows you to associate handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual success value or failure reason.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This lets asynchronous methods return values like synchronous methods: instead of immediately returning the final value, the asynchronous method returns a *promise* to supply the value at some point in the future.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The *eventual state* of a pending promise can either be *fulfilled* with a value or *rejected* with a reason (error).
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] When either of these options occur, the associated handlers queued up by a promise's `then` method are called.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] If the promise has already been fulfilled or rejected when a corresponding handler is attached, the handler will be called, so there is no race condition between an asynchronous operation completing and its handlers being attached.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A promise is said to be *settled* if it is either fulfilled or rejected, but not pending.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] (Flowchart showing how the Promise state transitions between pending, fulfilled, and rejected via then/catch handlers.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A pending promise can become either fulfilled or rejected.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] If fulfilled, the "on fulfillment" handler, or first parameter of the then() method, is executed and carries out further asynchronous actions.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] You will also hear the term *resolved* used with promises — this means that the promise is settled or "locked-in" to match the eventual state of another promise, and further resolving or rejecting it has no effect.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The States and fates document from the original Promise proposal contains more details about promise terminology.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Colloquially, "resolved" promises are often equivalent to "fulfilled" promises, but as illustrated in "States and fates", resolved promises can be pending or rejected as well.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This promise is already *resolved* at the time when it's created (because the `resolveOuter` is called synchronously), but it is resolved with another promise, and therefore won't be *fulfilled* until 1 second later, when the inner promise fulfills.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In practice, the "resolution" is often done behind the scenes and not observable, and only its fulfillment or rejection are.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] `Promise` itself has no first-class protocol for cancellation, but you may be able to directly cancel the underlying asynchronous operation, typically using `AbortController`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The promise methods `then()`, `catch()`, and `finally()` are used to associate further action with a promise that becomes settled.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method takes up to two arguments; the first argument is a callback function for the fulfilled case of the promise, and the second argument is a callback function for the rejected case.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The `catch()` and `finally()` methods call `then()` internally and make error handling less verbose.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] For example, a `catch()` is really just a `then()` without passing the fulfillment handler.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] As these methods return promises, they can be chained.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] We will use the following terminology: *initial promise* is the promise on which `then` is called; *new promise* is the promise returned by `then`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The two callbacks passed to `then` are called *fulfillment handler* and *rejection handler*, respectively.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The settled state of the initial promise determines which handler to execute.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The completion of the handler determines the settled state of the new promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] For example, in the code above, if `myPromise` rejects, `handleRejectedA` will be called, and if `handleRejectedA` completes normally (without throwing or returning a rejected promise), the promise returned by the first `then` will be fulfilled instead of staying rejected.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Therefore, if an error must be handled immediately, but we want to maintain the error state down the chain, we must throw an error of some type in the rejection handler.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] On the other hand, in the absence of an immediate need, we can leave out error handling until the final `catch()` handler.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Each time, JavaScript picks a job from the queue and executes it to completion.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The jobs are defined by the executor of the `Promise()` constructor, the handlers passed to `then`, or any platform API that returns a promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The promises in a chain represent the dependency relationship between these jobs.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] When a promise settles, the respective handlers associated with it are added to the back of the job queue.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A promise can participate in more than one chain.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] For the following code, the fulfillment of `promiseA` will cause both `handleFulfilled1` and `handleFulfilled2` to be added to the job queue.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Because `handleFulfilled1` is registered first, it will be invoked first.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] An action can be assigned to an already settled promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In this case, the action is added immediately to the back of the job queue and will be performed when all existing jobs are completed.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Therefore, an action for an already "settled" promise will occur only after the current synchronous code completes and at least one loop-tick has passed.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This guarantees that promise actions are asynchronous.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The JavaScript ecosystem had made multiple Promise implementations long before it became part of the language.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Despite being represented differently internally, at the minimum, all Promise-like objects implement the *Thenable* interface.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A thenable implements the `.then()` method, which is called with two callbacks: one for when the promise is fulfilled, one for when it's rejected.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To interoperate with the existing Promise implementations, the language allows using thenables in place of promises.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] For example, `Promise.resolve` will not only resolve promises, but also trace thenables.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method is responsible for scheduling the execution of the provided `onFulfilled` and `onRejected` callbacks.
