[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] All these methods take an iterable of promises (thenables, to be exact) and return a new promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] They all support subclassing, which means they can be called on subclasses of `Promise`, and the result will be a promise of the subclass type.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To do so, the subclass's constructor must implement the same signature as the `Promise()` constructor — accepting a single `executor` function that can be called with the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks as parameters.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The subclass must also have a `resolve` static method that can be called like `Promise.resolve()` to resolve values to promises.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Note that JavaScript is single-threaded by nature, so at a given instant, only one task will be executing, although control can shift between different promises, making execution of the promises appear concurrent.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Parallel execution in JavaScript can only be achieved through worker threads.
