[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Promise"`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Appends a rejection handler callback to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the callback if it is called, or to its original fulfillment value if the promise is instead fulfilled.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Appends a handler to the promise, and returns a new promise that is resolved when the original promise is resolved.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The handler is called when the promise is settled, whether fulfilled or rejected.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Appends fulfillment and rejection handlers to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the called handler, or to its original settled value if the promise was not handled (i.e., if the relevant handler `onFulfilled` or `onRejected` is not a function).
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In this example, we use `setTimeout(...)` to simulate async code.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In reality, you will probably be using something like XHR or an HTML API.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This example shows diverse techniques for using Promise capabilities and diverse situations that can occur.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To understand this, start by scrolling to the bottom of the code block, and examine the promise chain.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Upon provision of an initial promise, a chain of promises can follow.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The chain is composed of `.then()` calls, and typically (but not necessarily) has a single `.catch()` at the end, optionally followed by `.finally()`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In this example, the promise chain is initiated by a custom-written `new Promise()` construct; but in actual practice, promise chains more typically start with an API function (written by someone else) that returns a promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The example function `tetheredGetNumber()` shows that a promise generator will utilize `reject()` while setting up an asynchronous call, or within the call-back, or both.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The function `promiseGetWord()` illustrates how an API function might generate and return a promise in a self-contained manner.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Note that the function `troubleWithGetNumber()` ends with a `throw`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] That is forced because a promise chain goes through all the `.then()` promises, even after an error, and without the `throw`, the error would seem "fixed".
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This is a hassle, and for this reason, it is common to omit `onRejected` throughout the chain of `.then()` promises, and just have a single `onRejected` in the final `catch()`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Comprehension is enhanced by seeing the errors actually occur.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To force more errors, change the `threshold` values.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This small example shows the mechanism of a `Promise`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The `testPromise()` method is called each time the `<button>` is clicked.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] It creates a promise that will be fulfilled, using `setTimeout()`, to the promise count (number starting from 1) every 1-3 seconds, at random.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The `Promise()` constructor is used to create the promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The fulfillment of the promise is logged, via a fulfill callback set using `p1.then()`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A few logs show how the synchronous part of the method is decoupled from the asynchronous completion of the promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] By clicking the button several times in a short amount of time, you'll even see the different promises being fulfilled one after another.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Another example using `Promise` and `XMLHttpRequest` to load an image is shown below.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Each step is commented on and allows you to follow the Promise and XHR architecture closely.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A settings object is an environment that provides additional information when JavaScript code is running.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This includes the realm and module map, as well as HTML specific information such as the origin.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] The incumbent settings object is tracked in order to ensure that the browser knows which one to use for a given piece of user code.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To better picture this, we can take a closer look at how the realm might be an issue.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] A **realm** can be roughly thought of as the global object.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] What is unique about realms is that they hold all of the necessary information to run JavaScript code.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This includes objects like `Array` and `Error`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] Each settings object has its own "copy" of these and they are not shared.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] That can cause some unexpected behavior in relation to promises.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In order to get around this, we track something called the **incumbent settings object**.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This represents information specific to the context of the user code responsible for a certain function call.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] To illustrate this a bit further we can take a look at how an `<iframe>` embedded in a document communicates with its host.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] In the above example, the inner text of the `<iframe>` will be updated only if the incumbent settings object is tracked.
[src:inquirer-prompts/global-objects-promise] This is because without tracking the incumbent, we may end up using the wrong environment to send the message.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] A collection of common interactive command line user interfaces.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Inquirer recently underwent a rewrite from the ground up to reduce the package size and improve performance.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The previous version of the package is still maintained (though not actively developed), and offered hundreds of community contributed prompts that might not have been migrated to the latest API.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] If this is what you're looking for, the previous package is over here.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] See documentation for usage example and options documentation.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Launches an instance of the users preferred editor on a temporary file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Once the user exits their editor, the content of the temporary file is read as the answer.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The editor used is determined by reading the $VISUAL or $EDITOR environment variables.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Very similar to the `input` prompt, but with built-in number validation configuration option.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Need prompts in a language other than English?
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The `@inquirer/i18n` package is a drop-in replacement for `@inquirer/prompts` with built-in localization.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The root import automatically detects your locale from the `LANGUAGE`, `LC_ALL`, `LC_MESSAGES`, and `LANG` environment variables (falling back to the `Intl` API).
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] If no supported locale is found, English is used.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Built-in locales include English, French, Spanish, Chinese (Simplified), and Portuguese.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] You can also pin to a specific language via sub-path imports (e.g.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] `@inquirer/i18n/fr`), or use the `createLocalizedPrompts` and `registerLocale` APIs to add your own.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] See the full documentation for available languages and how to create a custom locale.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The API documentation is over here, and our testing utilities here.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] All inquirer prompts are a function taking 2 arguments.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The first argument is the prompt configuration (unique to each prompt).
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] The second is providing contextual or runtime configuration.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When providing an input stream or piping `process.stdin`, it's very likely you need to call `process.stdin.setRawMode(true)` before calling inquirer functions.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Node.js usually does it automatically, but when we shadow the stdin, Node can loss track and not know it has to.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] If the prompt isn't interactive (arrows don't work, etc), it's likely due to this.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] This can be done with either an `AbortController` or `AbortSignal`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When a user press `ctrl+c` to exit a prompt, Inquirer rejects the prompt promise.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] This is the expected behavior in order to allow your program to teardown/cleanup its environment.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When using `async/await`, rejected promises throw their error.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When unhandled, those errors print their stack trace in your user's terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] This isn't a great UX, which is why we highly recommend you to handle those errors gracefully.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] First option is to wrap your scripts in `try/catch`; like we do in our demo program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Or handle the error in your CLI framework mechanism; for example `Clipanion catch` method.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Lastly, you could handle the error globally with an event listener and silence it.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When asking many questions, you might not want to keep one variable per answer everywhere.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] In which case, you can put the answer inside an object.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Maybe some questions depend on some other question's answer.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] By default scripts ran from tools like `husky`/`lint-staged` might not run inside an interactive shell.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] In non-interactive shell, Inquirer cannot run, and users cannot send keypress events to the process.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] When using inquirer prompts with nodemon, you need to pass the `--no-stdin` flag for everything to work as expected.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Note that for most of you, you'll be able to use the new watch-mode built-in Node.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] This mode works out of the box with inquirer.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] Maybe some question configuration require to await a value.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] You can use Inquirer prompts directly in the shell via `npx`, which is useful for quick scripts or `package.json` commands.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] A community library, @inquirer-cli, exposes each prompt as a standalone CLI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] If you created a cool prompt, send us a PR adding it to the list below!
[src:inquirer-prompts/sboudrias-inquirer-js] An inquirer select that supports multiple selections and filtering/searching.
