[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:inquirer-prompts/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:inquirer-prompts/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
